Data Set Information¶

The dataset is obtained from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Estimation+of+obesity+levels+based+on+eating+habits+and+physical+condition+

There is a related article: https://reader.elsevier.com/reader/sd/pii/S2352340919306985?token=FBE9F3F02627BEC93C8C5B3D4AB21D2CFD7E1F1D5753D6E73C3D29782F8C5E15A1EFFB3D89167C60D99847BADBF46ABB&originRegion=us-east-1&originCreation=20210908201213

1. Businees Understanding¶

The data consists of 2111 instances and 17 attributes related to the physical activity, life style, and obesity.

The data consists of 2111 instances and 17 attributes related to the physical activity, life style, and obesity. Those attributes and their data type are the following:

A. Gender - binary
B. Age - ordinal
C. Height (meters) - interval (float)
D. Weight (kilograms) - interval (float)
E. Family history with overweight - binary
F. Frequent consumption of high caloric food (FAVC) - binary
G. Frequency of vegetables consumption (FCVC) - ordinal
H. Number of main meals (NCP) - ordinal
I. Consumption of food between meals (CAEC) - ordinal (entries will be converted to integers)
J. Smoke habit - binary
K. Daily consumption of water (CH2O) - ordinal
L. Monitoring of calories consumption (SCC) - binary
M. Frequency of physical activity during the week (FAF) - ordinal 
N. Time using technological devices (TUE) - ordinal
O. Alcohol consuption (CALC) - ordinal (entries will be converted)
P. Main transportation used (MTRANS) - ordinal (entries will be converted)
Q. Obesity level - ordinal (entries will be converted)

Note:¶

We decided to treat MTRANS entry as ordinal because it might interfere at one's weight (specially by comparing people who walk or ride a bike with the ones who use cars as main transportation)

This study can be used to identify the risk factors that result in obesity. The results can be used by insurance companies for example to know the individuals who are subject to obesity from the life style, family history, age, and gender. People with high level of obesity tend to be in higher risk of different diseases as: cardiovascular diseases and diabetes. Similarly, this can also be the interest of physicians.

Questions:¶

  • How does gender affect the level of obesity?
  • How does life style affect the level of obesity?
  • How does age affect the level of obesity?
  • How does family history with overweight affect the level of obesity?

There are no missing data found in the dataset. Thus, no imputations techniques are needed to be carried on the data. With respect to repeated data, there are a few duplicated instances. Before proceeding to examine how categories are distributed, it is important to consider the columns which entries are related to frequency of a given habit. For some categories, options are already displayed as integers(ordinal), they are:

  • Consuption of vegetables
  • Number of main meals
  • Water daily consuption
  • Physical activity frequency
  • Time using technological devices

However, for other entries, it is needed a conversion:

  • Food consuption between meals
  • Alcohol consuption
  • Transport used
  • Obesity level

For the obesity level, it used the Mass Body Index (MBI), $$MBI=\frac{weight}{height^2}$$

and results were classified using the following table:

Mass Body Index Obesity Level
< 18.5 underweight
18.5 - 24.9 normal
25.0 - 29.9 overweight
30.0 - 34.9 obesity I
35.0 - 39.9 obesity II
> 40.0 obesity III

Here, it is worth mention that, in the dataset, there are another entry Overweight II , and the article does not insert it in any MBI range. However, we will consider that someone classified with Overweight II has a MBI value greater than people classified as Overweight and smaller than the ones classified in Obesity I.

Aditionally, the categories which entries are yes/no must also be converted (binary) and we establish the following convention:

  • Yes = 1
  • No = 0

Note:¶

For frequency related categories, the values were converted to integers as follows: lower frequency entries were related to smaller integers (starting in 0, which means 'No' entry) and higher frequency entries, to the larger integers. However, the eating_vegetables category, which have its entry already displayed in ordinals, display the lowest frequency as a 1, instead of 0. In order to make our analysis more user-friendly, we will subtract 1 from each entry, in order to shift it for the used scale.

In [9]:
frequency=['no','Sometimes','Frequently','Always']
interval=range(4)
yn=['no','yes']
binary=range(2)
df.family_history.replace(to_replace=yn[:],
                          value=binary,
                          inplace=True)
df.high_caloric_food.replace(to_replace=yn[:],
               value=binary,
               inplace=True)
df.smoking.replace(to_replace=yn[:],
                value=binary,
                inplace=True)
df.monitoring_calories.replace(to_replace=yn[:],
              value=binary,
              inplace=True)
df.eating_bet_meals.replace(to_replace=frequency[:],
               value=interval,
               inplace=True)
df.alcohol_consumption.replace(to_replace=frequency[:],
               value=interval,
               inplace=True)
df.transportation.replace(to_replace=['Walking','Bike','Public_Transportation','Motorbike','Automobile'],
                 value=range(5),
                 inplace=True)
df.eating_vegetables=df.eating_vegetables[:]-1

As previously observed, there are nearly similar number of males and females in the group sample. This reflects that the difference in the distribution of the obesity level might be due to differences of gender and not a sampling problem. Males tend to occupy nearly all obesity type II, however females tend to occupy nearly all obesity level III.

Question 2: How does life style affect the level of obesity?¶

Question 2.1 : How does high caloric food intake affect the level of obesity?¶

In [19]:

In [20]:
plt.figure()
plt.title('High Caloric food consumption')
df.high_caloric_food.value_counts().plot(kind = 'bar')
Out[20]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'High Caloric food consumption'}>

From the graph above, we observe that all categories of obesity level (including the insufficient weight entry) present a higher amount of high caloric food consumption . However, there is no equal distribution of the sample between those have high-caloric intake and those don't. That is why it is difficult to determine the effect oh high caloric food intake based on the sample. Moreover, it is worth mention that, as oposite to other entries, in this category, there are just two possible answers, yes or no, and it is likely that most of people answered yes, though they might have different frequencies of high caloric food consumption.

Question 2.2 : How does the frequency of eating vegetables affect the level of obesity?¶

In [21]:
veg = pd.crosstab(df.obesity_level, df.eating_vegetables.astype(int))

veg.plot(kind='bar', stacked =True)
plt.xlabel('Obesity Level')
plt.title('Vegetables consumption related to the obesity level')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.show()

Considering levels up to Obesity II, vegetables consumption has a small correlation with obesity. Overweight and Obesity I and II entries tend to show a smaller frequency in vegetables consumption. For Obesity III, surprisingly 100% of the entries show the highest frequency in vegetables consumption, this is probably a sampling error.

Dimensionality reduction using Uniform Manifold Approximation and Projection (UMAP)¶

Dimensionality reduction is often employed when one is dealing with a large dataset. UMAP technique starts with a higher dimensional graph and then cluster similar entries in order to provide a lower dimensional version of it, with minimal loss of information.

In [35]:
df1 = df.drop(["Gender","screen_time","Age_range","eating_vegetables","monitoring_calories","transportation","alcohol_consumption",
              "eating_bet_meals","high_caloric_food"],axis=1)
In [36]:
df1.head(5)

In [37]:
import umap
import umap.plot
mapper = umap.UMAP().fit(df1) 
umap.plot.points(mapper, theme='fire')

*c* argument looks like a single numeric RGB or RGBA sequence, which should be avoided as value-mapping will have precedence in case its length matches with *x* & *y*.  Please use the *color* keyword-argument or provide a 2D array with a single row if you intend to specify the same RGB or RGBA value for all points.
Out[37]:
<AxesSubplot:>

This is the UMAP plot with similar categories clustered. As previously observed, our data is less correlated.
